–1444.","1432–1484":"1432–1484","1438–1482":"1438–1482","1444":"1444.","1432":"1432","1365":"1365.","before 25 September 1438":"prije 25. rujna 1438.","1484":"1484","1482":"1482","1438":"1438","Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland"},"cs":{"1365–1444":"1365–1444","1432–1484":"1432–1484","1438–1482":"1438–1482","1444":"1444","1432":"1432","1365":"1365","before 25 September 1438":"před 25. září 1438","1484":"1484","1482":"1482","1438":"1438","Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland"},"da":{"1365–1444":"1365–1444","1432–1484":"1432–1484","1438–1482":"1438–1482","1444":"1444","1432":"1432","1365":"1365","before 25 September 1438":"før 25. september 1438","1484":"1484","1482":"1482","1438":"1438","Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Paisley, Renfrewshire, Skotland"},"nl":{"1365–1444":"1365–1444","1432–1484":"1432–1484","1438–1482":"1438–1482","1444":"1444","1432":"1432","1365":"1365","before 25 September 1438":"vóór 25 september 1438","1484":"1484","1482":"1482","1438":"1438","Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Paisley, Renfrewshire, Schotland"},"en":{"1365–1444":"1365–1444","1432–1484":"1432–1484","1438–1482":"1438–1482","1444":"1444","1432":"1432","1365":"1365","before 25 September 1438":"before 25 September 1438","1484":"1484","1482":"1482","1438":"1438","Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Salisbury","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name primarily from Salesbury in Blackburn (Lancashire) but also occasionally from Salisbury (Wiltshire). The Lancashire placename derives from Old English <i>salh</i> ‘willow, sallow’ + <i>burg</i> ‘fortress’, while the Wiltshire placename arises from a shortened form of the Celtic placename <i>Sorviodunum</i> (from an unknown initial element + Celtic <i>dūno-</i> ‘fort’). In the Old English period the second element was dropped and <i>Sorvio-</i> (of unexplained etymology) became <i>Searo-</i> in Old English as the result of folk etymological association the Old English word <i>searu</i> ‘trick’; to this an explanatory <i>burh</i> ‘fortress, manor, town’ was added. The city is recorded in the Domesday Book as <i>Sarisberie</i>; the change of <i>-r-</i> to <i>-l-</i> is the result of later dissimilation."],"variants":[{"name":"Saulsbury","meanings":["English: variant of   Salisbury  ."]},{"name":"Saulsberry","meanings":["Altered form of English   Salisbury  ."]},{"name":"Salsbery","meanings":["English: variant of   Salisbury  ."]},{"name":"Salsbury","meanings":["English (Worcestershire): variant of   Salisbury  .","Jewish (American): adoption of the English surname (see 1 above) in place of   Salomon   or some other Jewish name beginning with <i>Sa-</i>."]},{"name":"Salsberry","meanings":["English: variant of   Salisbury  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Salisbury was born in 1365. She had at least 1 son with Alan John Cochran. She died in 1444, at the age of 79."},"et":{"1365–1444":"1365–1444","1432–1484":"1432–1484","1438–1482":"1438–1482","1444":"1444","1432":"1432","1365":"1365","before 25 September 1438":"enne 25. septembrit 1438","1484":"1484","1482":"1482","1438":"1438","Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1365–1444":"1365–1444","1432–1484":"1432–1484","1438–1482":"1438–1482","1444":"1444","1432":"1432","1365":"1365","before 25 September 1438":"ennen vuotta 25. syyskuuta 1438","1484":"1484","1482":"1482","1438":"1438","Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"1365–1444":"1365–1444","1432–1484":"1432